WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:04.880
Thank you, everyone. And I'm going to talk to you about a time that I accidentally made a

00:00:04.880 --> 00:00:09.520
production dashboard. I think this is something that will be familiar to many people in this room.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:15.200
So a bit of a story. I was working at a job, and I was working on a dashboard.

00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:20.000
We were looking at benchmarking reports, and it ran every night. I thought it was pretty cool at

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.920
first. We shared it with the engineering team. We started getting some questions. People seemed

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:29.120
interested in it. And I thought that was that. And then one morning, I was in a meeting, and the CEO

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:33.439
of the company said, oh, yeah, that thing, that thing's great. I look at it every morning before

00:00:33.439 --> 00:00:39.360
I even had my coffee. And that hit me like a ton of bricks. This was not a proof of concept anymore.

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:43.360
This was something that I needed to maintain. I needed to make sure it had accurate numbers,

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:47.439
or else I was going to get a call before I had my coffee, and they were one time zone ahead of me,

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:55.119
so that would be even worse. This is very common for data science. Data science projects transition

00:00:55.119 --> 00:00:59.040
from something that's a proof of concept, like is this even possible, let's try it out,

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:04.160
to something that is suddenly actually production, where it is something that people depend on

00:01:04.160 --> 00:01:09.519
day to day, very quickly, and sometimes in ways that we don't realize, and that's where things

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:13.120
get kind of dangerous. And a lot of the things that we've talked about in this whole session

00:01:13.120 --> 00:01:17.839
about how to productionize and what it means to be production are super important for things that

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:24.400
are production. So I like to think about this as living in the slush. I live in Chicago, and one

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:30.800
of the things that I had to learn when I moved to Chicago was that walking in slush can be really

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:34.800
dangerous. And so if you're walking in the rain, it's pretty easy. You don't have to take many

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:39.199
precautions. You can just wear normal shoes, maybe have an umbrella, and you're all good.

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:43.040
This is kind of the POC phase. Things are flowing. Things are great. You don't have to worry about

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:48.400
anything. When you're walking on slush, things are usually pretty fine as well. There's no big deal.

00:01:48.959 --> 00:01:53.040
You can walk. You're not worried about anything. But the thing that's dangerous with slush is that

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:58.559
sometimes underneath that slush, there's ice. And you can slip on ice if you're not careful or

00:01:58.559 --> 00:02:03.599
you're not wearing the right shoes. And data science is exactly like this. A lot of data

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:09.199
science operates in this slushy area where you're going from flowing with a proof of concept to

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:12.960
something that you actually need to harden like ice or else you're going to slip and fall and

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:19.119
you need to do something about that. So how do you tell that you're walking on ice?

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.800
The first and the most important thing is usage monitoring. And this is something that I know I

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:29.759
personally learned this lesson over and over in my career and I think everyone else here does the

00:02:29.759 --> 00:02:35.520
same thing. We as data scientists bring data driven decision making to our organizations.

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:42.160
And we don't sometimes take that same skill and that same approach with our own work. And this

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:46.240
is what bit me with my production dashboard. I didn't have any usage monitoring. I had no clue

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:52.000
who was looking at it. And so if we take things like usage monitoring, figure out who's looking

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.160
at our reports, our dashboards, our apps, when they're looking at it, how widespread that usage

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:03.199
is, that lets us know is this something that is just a cool proof of concept that I can just let

00:03:03.199 --> 00:03:09.600
be or is this something that is production I need to actually maintain? Usage monitoring is

00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:16.000
something that's not new. It's used throughout the software world. And it's used not just to see who

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.559
is looking at something, but also in detailed into features of who's clicking on this button,

00:03:20.559 --> 00:03:25.919
how long are they staying on this page? And this might sound scary, but it's easier than you would

00:03:25.919 --> 00:03:30.000
think. So if you've got a shiny app, you can write things to local storage when people click on

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:35.679
things, but there are packages like shiny telemetry that makes it super easy to collect this type of

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:43.520
usage data. If you've got Quarto documents or other static things that are hosted on some CDN,

00:03:43.679 --> 00:03:48.960
AWS, Posit Connect, you can use access logs to see who's seeing that. It's a little bit

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.800
less fidelity, but you can get some really good data out of something pretty simple.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:58.320
If your reports are something that's public or your organization allows it, you can use

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:01.919
things like Google Analytics and there are other analytics-style things that are basically

00:04:01.919 --> 00:04:07.600
JavaScript that logs when someone has actually loaded a screen. Quarto even has a really easy

00:04:07.600 --> 00:04:12.559
way of connecting this in. You just add in, there's like an identifier for Google Analytics that

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:17.279
will insert the JavaScript for you. You don't even have to think about it. And then,

00:04:17.279 --> 00:04:23.600
you know exactly who's looking at your dashboards. And if you have Posit Connect,

00:04:23.600 --> 00:04:30.160
this is actually baked in. Earlier today, Toph Allen shared the Connect Gallery,

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:36.000
and one of the items in the Connect Gallery is this Usage Dashboard. It lets you see on Connect

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.480
how popular your different items are that you've deployed, who's looking at things,

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:45.440
and you can even drill into the detail and see the time of day that people are looking at it,

00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:49.679
who's looking at it. And so, if I had this at the time, I would have seen, oh,

00:04:49.679 --> 00:04:53.519
CEO's logging in every single morning on this. I need to actually take this seriously.

00:04:55.040 --> 00:05:00.399
And so, in summary, once you're figuring out that you've got a thing that is popular,

00:05:01.279 --> 00:05:08.559
and you are in the side that is on the left side of this, which is, it's great. You're celebrating.

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:11.600
You've got a thing that's popular. You're providing value. You're excited.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:15.839
But there's also a lot of chaos going on. You're going to start getting feature requests. You've

00:05:15.839 --> 00:05:20.480
got to deal with, you know, there's a critical bug fix that you need. Someone wants some extra

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:25.679
data in there. And so, there's a real mixture of emotions, right? You've done something that's

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:31.440
successful, but now you've got all this extra work. On the other hand, if you have something

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:35.839
that was a cool proof of concept, you kind of said, hey, look, we can do this. This is the

00:05:35.839 --> 00:05:40.559
answer to this question. You don't have those feature requests. You don't have to put in the

00:05:40.559 --> 00:05:45.200
effort to make this a production grade. And that's great because you can sit and relax. The easiest

00:05:45.200 --> 00:05:49.839
work is work you don't have to do at all. Of course, that's also a little bit sad because

00:05:49.839 --> 00:05:53.359
you're like, well, people aren't really doing that. But the nice thing is you can take that

00:05:53.359 --> 00:05:56.320
energy and put it into the things that are actually important to maintain.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:02.079
So, what do we do now that we know we've got something that we have to maintain? We really

00:06:02.079 --> 00:06:07.519
need to invest time in it. I'm going to share a couple of techniques that are from the realm of

00:06:07.519 --> 00:06:13.119
software engineering, but bringing them into data science can really help improve the way that we

00:06:13.119 --> 00:06:18.000
maintain our apps. And the first two are kind of interrelated, but modularity and testing.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:25.200
And much like Tom's talk, a lot of this will be like not new to anybody, but it is important to

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:29.679
kind of think about this and especially do these things only when you actually have to.

00:06:29.679 --> 00:06:36.480
So, what is modularity? It is taking a long script that's just kind of a very procedural

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:41.359
set of code. There's a lot of nested if else and breaking it down into chunks that are logical

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:45.679
chunks. When you're prototyping something, it's really easy to kind of just write out the code,

00:06:45.679 --> 00:06:49.359
and that's kind of one of the superpowers. You can just write, see if it works. You're not

00:06:49.359 --> 00:06:54.480
worrying about abstraction layers or anything. But once you move into that production realm,

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:59.200
you do want to factor things out and do things like pull your data in one chunk or clean your

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:03.119
data in another chunk, fit a model, things like that. And frankly, these are even actually

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:07.200
probably a little bit too broad of chunks. You should have chunks that are smaller than that.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:13.359
But just illustratively, modularizing your code makes it much easier to figure out what's going

00:07:13.359 --> 00:07:17.839
wrong if something's going wrong. It also helps you focus in. And so, if what you're working on

00:07:17.839 --> 00:07:21.760
is your data cleaning code, you don't have to think about how am I getting this from the database or

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:25.760
where is this going in the model? You can say, okay, I just need to transform these columns,

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:30.640
I need to fill in NAs in this way and just focus on that. And modularity helps you do that

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.920
at a code level, but also just at a kind of what you're thinking about while you're working on that

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:42.239
code. And the best part of composability and decomposing things is that it makes testing

00:07:42.239 --> 00:07:46.720
these things a lot easier. So, you could test the thing on the left, you could have a big set of

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:51.839
inputs, run it through your whole script and check the outputs at the end, but that's going to get

00:07:51.839 --> 00:07:57.679
really messy really quickly. At its core, tests are, you've got some known inputs, you've got

00:07:57.679 --> 00:08:01.920
your function, you put your known inputs into the function and you compare it to outputs at the end.

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:07.519
If you're testing smaller chunks of code, the number of inputs, the number of options for the

00:08:07.519 --> 00:08:13.839
inputs, you can have relatively large, but they run relatively quickly and they're constrained

00:08:13.839 --> 00:08:18.239
because the domain is just your data cleaning step or just your model fitting step. And so,

00:08:18.239 --> 00:08:23.679
testing at the modular level is much easier than it is if you have a giant, long script that you

00:08:23.679 --> 00:08:30.959
need to test. The other nice thing about this is that I have found that using your tests as a kind

00:08:30.959 --> 00:08:36.799
of diagnosis tool of whether or not you factored your code correctly is really powerful. And so,

00:08:36.799 --> 00:08:42.960
if something is difficult to test, sometimes that's because the interface between the handoff

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:47.679
from one function to the next isn't quite clean. You've got a couple of things interplaying and so

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:52.640
you've got to kind of like test both at the same time. And that for me is a sign that maybe I need

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:57.919
to switch where things are actually happening between these two functions. And that's a

00:08:57.919 --> 00:09:03.840
virtuous cycle of testing and modularity and something that you can cleanly test is generally

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:11.359
cleanly factored. Okay. Now that you've got your tests, you can run them locally. That's great.

00:09:11.359 --> 00:09:15.359
That will confirm that you don't have a bug. And that's what this person is doing, running a bunch

00:09:15.359 --> 00:09:19.679
of tests all the time. They make a change, they run a test. But if you have code that's going to

00:09:19.679 --> 00:09:25.760
be shipped off somewhere, hosted on a service and run somewhere else, you can't just test on your

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:29.599
local laptop because you might have installed specific dependencies or something and not

00:09:29.599 --> 00:09:34.239
realize that's actually important to how you're actually running the code in production. And so,

00:09:34.239 --> 00:09:38.400
one of the first things that you need to do when you're testing is have your tests be run on some

00:09:38.400 --> 00:09:42.799
other computer. And so, you could call a colleague and be like, hey, can you run these tests for me?

00:09:43.599 --> 00:09:47.200
And that will work a few times. But if you're wanting to do that every single time you make a

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:52.559
change, you're going to turn a friend into an enemy very, very quickly. And so, ultimately,

00:09:52.559 --> 00:09:57.840
what you want to do is find a way to run that test on some computer that's somewhere else. It's not

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:03.919
your computer. And that's what cloud laptops are for. And that's exactly what continuous integration

00:10:03.919 --> 00:10:08.320
is. It's a container, which is a laptop in the cloud somewhere. It's not actually a laptop, but

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:14.320
it runs your tests on another computer and you don't have to bug your colleague to do that for

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:20.320
you. And that is effectively what continuous integration is. It is running your tests every

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:26.719
time you commit to your GitHub repository or other Git repository, spinning up in a container that's

00:10:26.719 --> 00:10:35.760
totally isolated, and it runs it constantly. And that is fantastic. So, continuous integration,

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:39.919
typically these days, is connected to your source control system. So, if you're using GitHub,

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:45.200
GitHub Actions is very integrated. It will spin up cloud laptops for you to run your tests. If

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:49.679
you're using GitLab, GitLab runners are the same thing. They're very, very similar. They have

00:10:49.679 --> 00:10:54.400
different syntaxes in the way that they work out. But if you're in a larger organization,

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:59.679
you might see other things like Travis CI or Circle CI or Jenkins. And other teams might

00:10:59.679 --> 00:11:04.320
already have these set up. And you can hook into these. And they do effectively the same thing.

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:09.679
They're not quite as integrated with your version control system, but they can do basically the same

00:11:09.679 --> 00:11:18.239
thing as GitHub Actions or GitLab runners. Okay. So, now that we've got our tests going,

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:23.840
we have a dashboard that's running. We've got a bunch of dependencies like ggplot2 and

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:30.640
dplyr and plumber, et cetera. What do we do as time marches on? One of the things that I have

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:35.679
always found really arduous when I have a long lived project is making sure that I am staying

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:42.479
up to date with my dependencies. One of the one approach you could take is to just constantly

00:11:42.479 --> 00:11:46.239
upgrade the dependencies bit by bit. Like every day check and see if there's something new. Bump

00:11:46.239 --> 00:11:51.840
it if there is. And this is really fantastic because when you do small steps with your

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:55.359
dependencies, frequently there's nothing that you have to change in your code. There are no

00:11:55.359 --> 00:12:00.239
breaking changes. You can just move on with your life. But if there are breaking changes,

00:12:00.239 --> 00:12:05.599
and you're only going from version 1 to version 2, that's usually a pretty easy there's one or

00:12:05.599 --> 00:12:10.559
two things that are changed. It's quick and easy to actually change that and keep up with the

00:12:10.559 --> 00:12:16.400
upgrade. But if you're jumping version 1 to version 8, that can be a huge pain. Because

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:20.640
you don't there are a bunch of things that changed in your dependency. Your code is interacting with

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:25.520
that. You have to parse through the change log of the dependency. But the nice thing about that

00:12:25.520 --> 00:12:29.520
is you're not sitting every day. I don't even need to update the dependencies. I need to update

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:37.280
dependencies. With modern CI, like GitHub actions, you can use what's called Dependabot. It scans

00:12:37.280 --> 00:12:41.679
your dependencies and sends you a PR every time there's an update or there's a critical bug.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:47.359
You can just accept it. If you got tests that are testing whether or not your code is running,

00:12:47.359 --> 00:12:52.719
the tests run on the Dependabot PR, if everything is good, you can just merge it.

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:57.520
And so that's basically having a bot do your constant updating for you, and you don't have

00:12:57.520 --> 00:13:02.320
to think about it. This is just one of the many, many fabulous things that you can do

00:13:03.039 --> 00:13:09.039
with modern CI. But it is fantastic, and it means that you're not worrying about dependency

00:13:09.039 --> 00:13:12.320
upgrades except for when you actually have to get in if you're out what changed.

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:17.520
And there are many other things that you can do once you realize you've got a production app.

00:13:18.719 --> 00:13:24.320
Many of the topics that we talked about here, and Joe will talk about what to do when you've got

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:29.039
REST APIs that are slowing down because you've got a lot of people that are poking at them suddenly.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:35.280
And so ultimately, what I want you to walk away from this is go from oops,

00:13:35.280 --> 00:13:39.359
I made a production dashboard, to yay, I made a production dashboard, and actually get to be

00:13:39.359 --> 00:13:42.960
happy about it, because you know you've got tools that you can maintain it, and you're

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:47.359
not spending time doing that on dashboards that aren't actually production, aren't actually

00:13:47.359 --> 00:13:54.719
popular. So with these tools, you can monitor the dashboards that you're building, know whether or

00:13:54.719 --> 00:13:59.919
not they're popular, and then for the ones that are actually popular, you can keep them running

00:13:59.919 --> 00:14:05.520
stably with modulization, testing, keep them up to date with things like dependency updates.

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:10.479
But again, most importantly, you only really need to do that if it truly is production. If

00:14:10.479 --> 00:14:14.000
you've got a proof of concept that was cool, answered some question, but nobody is looking

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.640
at it, you can go home. You're good to go. Thank you.

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:35.119
Thank you. I think we have time for a couple of questions. So first one, do you have any advice

00:14:35.119 --> 00:14:39.599
for someone who's trying to start modulizing their data code, but is trying to balance speed

00:14:39.599 --> 00:14:45.440
with best practices? Oh, that's complicated. I actually kind of want to know, speed there,

00:14:45.440 --> 00:14:51.119
is that speed of your energy or speed of the code itself? But I know you can't clarify.

00:14:51.119 --> 00:14:55.280
Yeah, that's how I would interpret it. Yeah, yeah, yeah. I would say start small.

00:14:55.919 --> 00:15:03.200
And especially, it sounds a little religious in some ways, but writing, doing your modularization

00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:07.440
and then writing your tests and using your tests as a confirmation that you've modularized well

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:13.359
is super powerful. And once you kind of fall into that circle, I have found it helps a lot.

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:21.119
Awesome. Do you have a favorite tracker for web analytics and why?

00:15:21.760 --> 00:15:24.159
Favorite tracker for web analytics? Yeah, for web analytics. Or do you

00:15:24.159 --> 00:15:27.919
tend to use open source tools like Shiny Logger and stuff?

00:15:27.919 --> 00:15:34.239
Yeah, it really depends on the context that you are, where you're deploying your app to. So if

00:15:34.239 --> 00:15:37.679
it's something that's public on the internet, I think Google Analytics is really fantastic.

00:15:38.640 --> 00:15:44.000
It's basically free. It works with a bunch of different things. If you've got a dashboard that's

